comments.commentText: Should we call this \u0060Endpoint\u0060 since that\u0027s the .ctor parameter name?

Although I think that makes sense, there is a lot of historical precedent across previous versions of the library and storage to where customers know and expect this name. I\u0027m ok to change it though if you feel strongly that we shouldn\u0027t factor this in.

I don\u0027t feel strongly about it, but I would say if this library was in Azure.Storage group, I would advocate that we need to string to Uri (blobs terminology). But we are trying to position tables as a data technology, not storage.

The other difference is Storage uses \u0060fooUri\u0060 in the .ctor so it matches \u0060Uri\u0060 as a property.  See https://apiview.dev/Assemblies/Review/77426af3f12a4487ab98859fca53a6dc#Azure.Storage.Blobs.BlobServiceClient
I\u0027m assuming we return \u0060null\u0060 if not found?

We actually return an \u0022empty\u0022 response ( \u0060new T();\u0060 ). Returning a null Response\u003CT\u003E is problematic, because the type coercion to T results in a strange and unexpected NRE.
Really?  How do I detect that as a customer?  That seems kind of hard to use.

comments.commentText: It parses an existing SasUri. Any concerns?

What\u0027s the scenario for it?  We considered this for Blobs but Jeff felt there wasn\u0027t a meaningful reason customers would want to clone a SAS.  Consider using \u0060sasUri\u0060 as the parameter name if you want to keep it.
I think this came from an earlier discussion - IIRC the scenario was that the developer has an existing SASUri and wants to modify it using the SasBuilder.
